---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Stove Philosophy | About">
  <main class="mx-auto min-h-screen max-w-5xl px-6 py-14 sm:py-20">
    <section>
      <p
        class="inline-flex rounded-full border border-fuchsia-300/30 bg-fuchsia-500/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium tracking-wide text-fuchsia-200"
      >
        About Stove Philosophy
      </p>
      <h1
        class="mt-5 max-w-3xl bg-gradient-to-r from-fuchsia-100 via-amber-100 to-cyan-100 bg-clip-text text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-transparent sm:text-6xl"
      >
        A completely serious history (that definitely happened)
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-lg">
        Scholars disagree on many things, but most agree Stove Philosophy began
        in 432 BCE, when a distracted cook in a tiny mountain kitchen forgot a
        pot of lentils for “just two minutes” and accidentally invented
        patience.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <article
        class="rounded-xl border border-amber-400/20 bg-amber-500/10 p-5"
      >
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Chapter I: The Great Simmering
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          Legend says the first Stove Sages gathered around a single burner and
          asked, “Should we turn this up?” After an 8-hour debate and one
          dramatic ladle gesture, they concluded: medium-low is the path to
          enlightenment.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article
        class="rounded-xl border border-indigo-400/20 bg-indigo-500/10 p-5"
      >
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Chapter II: The Preheating Schism
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          The community split into two factions: the Preheaters and the
          Toss-It-In-Now crowd. Peace returned only after the Toss-It-In-Now
          crowd produced twelve stuck pans and one deeply humbling apology tour.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article
        class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-400/20 bg-emerald-500/10 p-5 sm:col-span-2"
      >
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Chapter III: The Four Burners Treaty
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          In the year of the Boiled-Over Soup, the ancient Stoves declared that
          Family, Work, Health, and Friends could not all be on high at once.
          This radical concept was called “basic realism.” Civilizations
          prospered. Group chats improved. Burnt garlic incidents declined by
          23%.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article
        class="rounded-xl border border-rose-400/20 bg-rose-500/10 p-5 sm:col-span-2"
      >
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Chapter IV: The Leftover Prophecy
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          The final scroll warned: all food expires, including your emotional
          support cheese. This was never meant to inspire fear—only urgency. Use
          the good plate. Open the fancy oil. Text your friend back before the
          cilantro turns to sadness.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section
      class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-500/10 p-6"
    >
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white">Founding Timeline</h2>
      <ol class="relative mt-6 space-y-8 pl-8">
        <li class="relative">
          <span
            class="absolute -left-[2.15rem] top-1.5 h-4 w-4 rounded-full border-2 border-violet-200 bg-violet-500 shadow-[0_0_0_4px_rgba(139,92,246,0.25)]"
          ></span>
          <p
            class="inline-flex rounded-full border border-violet-300/30 bg-violet-400/10 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-violet-200"
          >
            432 BCE
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
            A lentil pot is forgotten, and patience is discovered right after
            mild panic.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="relative">
          <span
            class="absolute -left-[2.15rem] top-1.5 h-4 w-4 rounded-full border-2 border-violet-200 bg-violet-500 shadow-[0_0_0_4px_rgba(139,92,246,0.25)]"
          ></span>
          <p
            class="inline-flex rounded-full border border-violet-300/30 bg-violet-400/10 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-violet-200"
          >
            1187 CE
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
            The First Council of Preheaters formally outlaws “cold-pan
            optimism.”
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="relative">
          <span
            class="absolute -left-[2.15rem] top-1.5 h-4 w-4 rounded-full border-2 border-violet-200 bg-violet-500 shadow-[0_0_0_4px_rgba(139,92,246,0.25)]"
          ></span>
          <p
            class="inline-flex rounded-full border border-violet-300/30 bg-violet-400/10 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-violet-200"
          >
            2009 CE
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
            The Leftover Prophecy is translated into modern language: “Label
            your containers, you absolute gremlin.”
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section
      class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-500/10 p-6"
    >
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white">Modern Practice</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
        Today, Stove Philosophy continues in kitchens everywhere: in every
        careful stir, every rescued sauce, and every brave decision to lower the
        heat instead of pretending things are “probably fine.”
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
        If you have ever said, “It&apos;s not burned, it&apos;s caramelized,”
        you are already one of us.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
